  "title": "Speed of Sound Waves",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Sound",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Sound</h3><p>Sound waves are mechanical waves. They require a medium for their propagation i.e. they cannot propagate in vacuum.</p><p>Sound is produced in a material by a vibrating source. Sound waves constitute alternate compression and rarefaction pulses travelling in the medium. The compression travels in the medium at a speed, which depends on the elastic and inertial properties of the medium.</p><p>The description in terms of pressure wave is more appropriate than the description in terms of the displacement wave as far as sound properties are concerned.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dbdec03b9dcaf1afe3d6"
    },
    {
      "title": "Speed of Longitudinal Waves ",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Speed of a Longitudinal Wave</strong></h3><p>First we calculate the speed at which a longitudinal pulse propagates through a fluid. We will apply Newton's second law to the motion of an element of the fluid and from this we derive the wave equation.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"453\" height=\"113\"></p><p>Consider a fluid element 'ab' confined to a tube of cross sectional area $\\text{S}$ as shown in figure. The element has a thickness $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }x$. We assume that the equilibrium pressure of the fluid is ${{P}_{0}}$. Because of the disturbance, the section ' $a$ ' of the element moves a distance y from its mean position and section 'b' moves a distance $y+\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }y$ to a new position $b$ '. The pressure on the left side of the element becomes ${{\\text{P}}_{0}}+\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{1}}$ and on the right side it becomes ${{\\text{P}}_{0}}+\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{2}}$. If $\\rho $ is the equilibrium density, the mass of the element is $\\rho S\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }x$. (When the element moves its mass does not change, even though its volume and density do change).</p><p>The net force acting on the element is,</p><p>$\\text{F}=\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{1}}-\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{S}$</p><p>and its acceleration is $a=\\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}y}{\\partial {{t}^{2}}}$</p><p>Thus, Newton's second law applied to the motion of the element is</p><p>$\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{1}}-\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{S}=\\rho \\text{S }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ x}\\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\partial {{\\text{t}}^{2}}}$</p><p>Next we divide both sides by $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ x}$ and note that in the limit as $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ x}\\to 0$ we have $\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{1}}-\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{P}}_{2}} \\right)/\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ x}$</p><p>$\\to \\partial \\text{P}/\\partial \\text{x},\\text{Eq}\\cdot $ (i) then takes the form $-\\frac{\\partial \\text{P}}{\\partial \\text{x}}=\\rho \\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}\\text{y}}{\\partial {{\\text{t}}^{2}}}$ …(ii)</p><p>The excess pressure $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ P}$ may be written as $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ P}=-\\text{B}\\frac{\\partial \\text{y}}{\\partial \\text{x}}$</p><p>When this is used in Eq. (ii), we obtain the wave equation</p><p>$\\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}y}{\\partial {{x}^{2}}}=\\frac{\\rho }{B}\\cdot \\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}y}{\\partial {{t}^{2}}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ or }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}y}{\\partial {{t}^{2}}}=\\frac{B}{\\rho }\\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}y}{\\partial {{x}^{2}}}$</p><p>Comparing this equation with the wave equation</p><p>$\\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}y}{\\partial {{t}^{2}}}={{v}^{2}}\\frac{{{\\partial }^{2}}y}{\\partial {{x}^{2}}}$</p><p>We have $v=\\sqrt{\\frac{B}{\\rho }}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ (speed }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ longitudinal }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ wave }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ in }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ a }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ fluid) }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$</p><p>This is the speed of longitudinal waves within a gas or a liquid.</p><p>When a longitudinal wave propagates in a solid rod or bar, the rod expands sideways slightly when it is compressed longitudinally and the speed of a longitudinal wave in a rod is given by</p><p>$v=\\sqrt{\\frac{Y}{\\rho }}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ speed }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ a }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ longitudinal }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ wave }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ in }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ a }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ solid }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ rod }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\right)$</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dbdec03b9dcaf1afe3d7"
    },
    {
      "title": "Velocity of Sound in Ideal Gas ",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Velocity of Sound in an Ideal Gas</strong></h3><p>The motion of sound wave in air is adiabatic. In the case of an ideal gas, the relation between pressure $\\text{P}$ and volume $\\text{V}$ during an adiabatic process is given by</p><p>$\\text{P}{{\\text{V}}^{\\gamma }}=\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ constant }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$</p><p>Where $\\gamma $ is the ratio of the heat capacity at constant pressure to that at constant volume.</p><p>After differentiating, we get</p><p>${{\\text{V}}^{\\gamma }}\\frac{\\text{dP}}{\\text{dV}}+\\gamma \\text{P}{{\\text{V}}^{\\gamma -1}}=0$</p><p>Since $B=-\\frac{vdP}{dV}=\\gamma \\text{P}$</p><p>using the gas equation $\\frac{P}{\\rho }=\\frac{RT}{M}$ where $M$ is the molar mass.</p><p>Thus $\\text{v}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma \\text{RT}}{\\text{M}}}(\\text{T}=$ temperature is Kelvin $)$.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dbdec03b9dcaf1afe3d8"
    },
    {
      "title": "Effect of Temperature on Velocity",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Effect of Temperature on Velocity</strong></h3><p>If the specific volume of gas is v. The velocity of sound = $\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma \\text{P}}{\\rho }}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma \\text{RT}}{\\text{M}}}$</p><p>If ${{c}_{1}}$ and ${{c}_{2}}$ be the velocities of sound in a gas at temperatures $t_{1}^{\\circ }\\text{C}$ and $t_{2}^{\\circ }\\text{C}$ and ${{\\text{P}}_{1}}$ and ${{\\text{P}}_{2}}$ the respective pressures and ${{V}_{1}}$ and ${{V}_{2}}$ the specific volumes at these temperatures, ratio of the two velocities of sound is</p><p>$\\frac{{{\\text{v}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{v}}_{2}}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{{{\\text{P}}_{1}}{{\\text{V}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{P}}_{2}}{{\\text{V}}_{2}}}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{R}{{\\text{T}}_{1}}}{\\text{RT}}}$ where $\\text{T}$ and ${{\\text{T}}_{2}}$ are the absolute temperatures.</p><p>Hence, $\\text{ v}\\propto \\sqrt{\\text{T}}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\frac{{{\\text{v}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{v}}_{2}}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{273+{{\\text{t}}_{1}}}{273+{{\\text{t}}_{2}}}}$</p><p>If ${{\\text{v}}_{\\text{t}}}$ and ${{\\text{v}}_{0}}$ are the velocities at $\\text{tC}$ and $0\\text{C}$, then $\\frac{{{\\text{v}}_{\\text{t}}}}{{{\\text{v}}_{\\text{o}}}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{273+\\text{t}}{273}}$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow {{\\text{v}}_{\\text{t}}}={{\\text{v}}_{0}}{{\\left( 1+\\frac{\\text{t}}{273} \\right)}^{1/2}}$</p><p>when $\\text{t}$ is small</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} \\frac{{{\\text{v}}_{\\text{t}}}}{{{\\text{v}}_{0}}} &amp; \\approx \\left( 1+\\frac{\\text{t}}{546} \\right) \\\\ \\Rightarrow {{\\text{v}}_{\\text{t}}} &amp; ={{\\text{v}}_{0}}\\left( 1+\\frac{\\text{t}}{546} \\right) \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Put ${{\\text{v}}_{0}}=332\\text{ m}/\\text{s}$ at $0\\text{C}$</p><p>${{\\text{v}}_{\\text{t}}}=\\left( 332+0.61\\text{t} \\right)\\text{m}/\\text{s}$</p><p>This implies that for small temperature variations at $0\\text{C}$, velocity of sound changes by 0.61 $\\text{m}/\\text{s}$ when temperature changes by $1\\text{C}$.</p>",
      "position": 3,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dbdec03b9dcaf1afe3d9"
    },
    {
      "title": "Effect of Pressure and Humidity",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Effect of Pressure and Humidity</h3><p><strong>Effect of pressure</strong></p><p>In a gas; $\\text{v}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma \\text{P}}{\\rho }}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma \\text{RT}}{\\text{M}}}$ change in pressure has no effect on velocity of sound in a gas, so long as temperature is constant because; $\\frac{\\text{P}}{\\rho }=$ constant; as long as temperature is constant.</p><p><strong>Effect of relative humidity</strong></p><p>When humidity increases, there is an increase in the relative number of water molecules and hence a decrease in molar mass, and the speed of sound increases.</p>",
      "position": 4,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dbdfc03b9dcaf1afe3da"
    }
  ],
